	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I have 3 arcade cabinets, another hobby I jumped into about a year ago (it was inevitable).
<br />
<br />First one was originally Boot Camp by Konami (dual trackballs, with a lower shelf for more buttons).  But at some point was converted to Street Fighter 2 CE.  Cabinet was painted grey, you can still see the outline of the original artwork though.  I replaced the board with my old PC, using a Jamma adapter, replaced the joysticks and buttons with all new stuff, cleaned the coin mechs, fixed the marquee light (needed a new starter), added a subwoofer (also drives the 2 original speakers), then I wired a volume pot in-line with that and mounted it onto the front of the cabinet, using a pre-existing but convenient hole (easy to reach, but hard to bump into accidentally).  Pretty decent cabinet, 2 players, 6 buttons each, and on the lower metal control panel 'shelf' if I wanted to, I could install up to 8 (!) more buttons.  Monitor needs a cap kit, haven't done it yet.
<br />
<br />The second one really is a project (still on-going).  It was also a Konami cabinet, a 4-player one that I think was Sunset Riders originally (just guessing from the colors on a tiny piece of the art that remains).  It had been converted to Police Trainer, and the person I got it from (was just an empty cabinet) was converting it to NFL Blitz but quit part-way through it, after sanding the top of the (huge) control panel.  I had planned to sand it all, prime it, paint it, but I later said screw that, and will just sand and prime the parts that need it, then paint over it all.  But it's still sitting at my dad's house, as there's no way I can paint it here (without hauling it up and down stairs repeatedly).  Too cold to mess with it now, not enough daylight either (thanks to Indiana moving onto the retarded "daylight saving time" so now it's always dark when I get home from work).  But I picked up an old 25" monitor for that one, haven't even fired it up yet.  I bought a TMNT marquee to put on it, heheh.  Not sure what I'll do for the control panel artwork yet, definitely something polycarbonate though because it cleans up so easily.
<br />
<br />The 3rd cabinet, no big surprise, is a Playchoice-10 (single monitor version).  Decent shape, has 10 games.  Monitor also needs a cap kit, picture is noticeably shrunken vertically.  I also have a VS Dualsystem board that I might use with this eventually.  Other than the cap kit, the main other plan I have for this is to wire a zapper to it.  The arcade light guns sell for more than I want to pay.
<br />
<br />Later on I still want to look for more cheap cabinets!  Good thing I have a big basement.
<br />
<br />A friend's stepdad used to have Defender, I played the hell out of it over there and really grew to like it.  On my SF2 cabinet I play Robotron more than anything else.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
