	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You have to pick your hardware though. I'd go for Defender's hardware, it has bankswitching. Stargate doesn't have bankswitching. And then there's the special chips for moving memory or not, you can homebrew on that too. One good thing is that sound is on a seperate board and all you do is send codes to it and it plays it. Bad thing is unless your good, it's only one channel, since it's a 8-Bit DAC.
<br />
<br />
<br />And one BAD thing about this is that the RAM thats use able is scattered throughout it. It has X bytes on screen, X bytes in HBLANK, X bytes on screen, X Bytes in HBLANK so you have to calculate what's useable and what's not. Then you'll probably have to do what they did with defender and put the stack on the left side of the screen and adjust it off.
<br />
<br />
<br />If you homebrew, just use a good 6809 assembler and then a 6800 for the sound board. That should make you good for a while. 6809 is very fun to code although this platform might be difficult, it'll be a cool adventure. If you do this you should keep me posted. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" />

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


